%N A282939 Maximum number of straight lines required to draw the boundary of any polyomino with n squares.
%C A282939 For n >= 7, polyominoes can have holes whose boundaries are also included.
%C A282939 An n-omino in the shape of a "staircase" has 2n boundary edges, so a(n) >= 2n.
%C A282939 If we "join" copies of the X pentomino (sharing one square) then we can do better than the above lower bound. This gives us a(4k+1) >= 8k+4, for any k >= 0.
%C A282939 It appears that a(n) = 2*n+2 for n (mod 4) == 1, otherwise a(n) = 2*n, which coincides with the lower bounds above. - _Lars Blomberg_, Nov 09 2017
%C A282939 The conjecture that a(n) = 2*n+2 for n (mod 4) == 1, otherwise a(n) = 2*n, is proven. See link. - _John Mason_, Jun 08 2021
%H A282939 John Mason, <a href="/A282939/a282939.pdf">Proof of conjecture</a>
%e A282939 For n=1, we have the monomino (single square), so a(1)=4.
%e A282939 For n=2, we have the domino, so a(2)=4.
%e A282939 For n=3, we have the L tromino, so a(3)=6.
%e A282939 For n=4, we have the T and S tetrominoes, so a(4)=8.
%e A282939 For n=5, we have the X pentomino, so a(5)=12.
